{
  "title": "Scales",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "heading-one",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Scales ‚Äì Finding Good Sounds"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "First, ask yourself: why does music sound ‚Äúgood‚Äù? Every day we are surrounded by all kinds of noises‚Äîcar horns, office keyboard clicks‚Äîyet these sounds are not as ‚Äúpleasant‚Äù as music. Why?"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "These questions lead us to the topic of ‚Äúscales‚Äù in music theory. Scales are also what TV talent shows call ‚Äúkeys‚Äù or ‚Äúmodes‚Äù; they are the bedrock of music."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Recall junior-high physics: sound is produced by vibration. The faster an object vibrates, the ‚Äúhigher‚Äù the pitch. A bee flaps faster, the buzz sounds ‚Äúhigher‚Äù and harsher."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "img",
      "id": "ee2a7e37-a566-429f-8106-d41b8476d31d",
      "url": "https://luv-club.oss-cn-chengdu.aliyuncs.com/be717b5a-8b49-434a-a936-2877d9496e07-image.png",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "So ‚Äúpitch‚Äù is essentially vibration frequency."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Human ears are naturally fond of certain frequencies. "
        },
        {
          "text": "The underlying principle of music is that simple",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": ". As mentioned in the prologue, ancient people found that striking specific pitches sounded ‚Äúnice‚Äù, but they only had empirical knowledge, no standards or rules. Random trial-and-error produced uneven quality and low efficiency, so people began searching for standards and patterns to create pleasant, smooth music."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Generations explored and passed down experience, discovering that if the pitches within a set obeyed certain ratio relationships, the music felt harmonious and smooth. We call such a set a ‚Äúscale‚Äù."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
