    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Besides inventing ‚Äúscales‚Äù, our predecessors also created ‚Äúnote names‚Äù. As said, pitch is fundamentally ‚Äúfrequency‚Äù; higher frequency sounds sharper, lower frequency sounds deeper. We name specific frequencies for convenience‚Äîe.g., 440 Hz is called A. If two pitches‚Äô frequencies "
        },
        {
          "text": "differ by exactly double",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": ", e.g. 261 Hz "
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "4a367750-8bc6-436f-bf2a-c13fae7fe5c2",
          "noteStr": "C4",
          "editing": false,
          "children": [
            {
              "text": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " and 522 Hz "
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "22c52eb6-60de-4958-a8c1-b1c9b130cccc",
          "noteStr": "C5",
          "editing": false,
          "children": [
            {
              "text": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": ", the distance between them is an ‚Äúoctave‚Äù. The number after C4, C5 etc. means the right note is one octave higher; they sound like the same pitch class. Click ‚Äúplay‚Äù below to feel the consonance of notes an octave apart:"
